{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784210833262,"sessionID":"ses_094c57e18ffemFIYitl0QMkdbq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_EcIAIhh6iVWGdEwr2OKp9zL4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/scripts/test_create_diff.py","pattern":"cleanup|cmd_cleanup|manifest|snapshot","include":"test_create_diff.py"},"output":"No files found","metadata":{"matches":0,"truncated":false},"title":"cleanup|cmd_cleanup|manifest|snapshot","time":{"start":1784210833234,"end":1784210833261}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09a0b1a9d171929b016a58e5910c288191be1c368c32596751"}},"id":"prt_f6b40bf040014Taa6tR6R48LjP","sessionID":"ses_094c57e18ffemFIYitl0QMkdbq","messageID":"msg_f6b4036d7001RFUSs0WhB9jSBR"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784210833273,"sessionID":"ses_094c57e18ffemFIYitl0QMkdbq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_L49F1FC2ubd2PWJgQgCsQVoX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff","pattern":"container-name:report|@container report|cqi|unsupported|fallback","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 69 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/SKILL.md:\n  Line 146: ### Explicit-pair flow (fallback — no stored state needed)\n\n  Line 172: Add `--json` to `compare`, `compare-pair`, `capabilities`, or `status` for a structured summary. Exit codes: `0` success · `2` usage error · `3` unsupported/limited format with no fallback · `4` missing baseline snapshot · `5` I/O or extraction failure. Map these to actionable messages rather than swallowing them.\n\n  Line 188: `text*` (PDF) requires a local extractor — poppler's `pdftotext` or the `pypdf`/`pdfplumber` package. Run `capabilities` to see what is available; when none is, the engine says so and offers the explicit-pair fallback with pre-extracted text. Full detail: `references/capabilities-and-fidelity.md`.\n\n  Line 201: - Offer the explicit-pair fallback when no valid baseline exists.\n\n  Line 207: - Never claim a diff was produced when the format was unsupported and no fallback ran.\n\n  Line 214: - When the document format is unsupported and no explicit pre-extracted pair can be provided.\n\n  Line 236: - The baseline was captured before the edit, or the explicit-pair fallback was used, and the source file is unchanged.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/changelog/v1.1.0.0.md:\n  Line 16:   - Honest refusal of unsupported input: binary office/media/archive formats (`.xlsx`, `.pptx`, `.png`, `.zip`, …) and any file with binary content exit `3` rather than being raw-byte \"text\"-diffed into a meaningless report; unknown *text-like* extensions still fall back to text with a stated assumption.\n\n  Line 18:   - Content-addressed baseline snapshots (`snapshot`/`compare`), an explicit-pair fallback (`compare-pair`), and lifecycle commands (`status`, `cleanup`, `capabilities`).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/references/cli-reference.md:\n  Line 93: | `3` | Unsupported/limited format with no fallback (e.g. PDF with no extractor). |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/references/workflow.md:\n  Line 3: description: The capture-before-edit invariant, the automatic snapshot flow, the explicit-pair fallback, snapshot storage, and cleanup lifecycle for create-diff.\n\n  Line 34: ## Explicit-pair flow (fallback)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/feature-catalog/safety-and-capabilities/capability-tier-reporting.md:\n  Line 20: This is the honesty layer a caller consults before trusting a comparison. `capabilities` answers \"what can this compare, and how well\" up front, and the same tier information is what stamps every report summary. The critical behavior is that it never overstates: a format the engine cannot handle fully is reported at its true tier, and an outright unsupported input exits `3` with an actionable message rather than fabricating a diff. The one environment-dependent answer is the PDF extractor, which is detected at runtime.\n\n  Line 28: The reporting is wired to the engine's actual behavior, not a static list: when a caller asks to compare an unsupported or limited format with no fallback, the run exits `3` with a message that both explains the limit and points at the explicit-pair fallback. That is what keeps a limited-fidelity or impossible comparison from being silently presented as a complete one.\n\n  Line 38: | `scripts/create_diff.py` | Script | `capabilities [--json]` prints the format matrix and detected PDF extractor; unsupported/limited formats exit `3` with an actionable message pointing at the explicit-pair fallback |\n\n  Line 45: | `manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md` | Manual playbook | SAFE-004 (capability reporting and unsupported handling) and CMP-003 (conditional PDF) |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md:\n  Line 200: With an extractor present, expect a `pdf, tier text*` report; with none, expect exit `3` and an actionable message pointing to the explicit-pair fallback.\n\n  Line 248: ### SNAP-002 | Missing baseline routes to fallback\n\n  Line 251: Verify that `compare` with no stored baseline exits `4` and that the explicit-pair fallback works instead.\n\n  Line 258: Desired user-visible outcome: a clear \"no baseline\" message and a working fallback path.\n\n  Line 261: > **Feature File:** [SNAP-002](snapshot/missing-baseline-fallback.md)\n\n  Line 340: ### SAFE-004 | Capability reporting and unsupported handling\n\n  Line 343: Verify that `capabilities` reports the format matrix and detected PDF extractor, and that unsupported/limited cases fail honestly.\n\n  Line 348: Run `capabilities` (and `capabilities --json`); expect the five formats with tiers and the detected PDF extractor; confirm an unsupported case exits `3` rather than fabricating a diff.\n\n  Line 350: Desired user-visible outcome: an accurate capability matrix and honest failure on unsupported input.\n\n  Line 353: > **Feature File:** [SAFE-004](safety/capability-and-unsupported-handling.md)\n\n  Line 378: | SNAP-002 | Missing baseline routes to fallback | SNAPSHOT | [SNAP-002](snapshot/missing-baseline-fallback.md) |\n\n  Line 383: | SAFE-004 | Capability reporting and unsupported handling | SAFETY | [SAFE-004](safety/capability-and-unsupported-handling.md) |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/feature-catalog/feature-catalog.md:\n  Line 97: Compares two explicit files with no stored state — the fallback when no baseline exists or when comparing two arbitrary versions.\n\n  Line 151: `capabilities` prints (or emits `--json`) the format matrix and detected PDF extractor; unsupported formats exit `3` with an actionable message and the explicit-pair fallback.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/references/capabilities-and-fidelity.md:\n  Line 25: | `unsupported` | No reliable local extraction available. |\n\n  Line 37: Unknown *text-like* extensions are treated as plain text, and the report carries a fidelity warning saying so, so the assumption can be corrected. Known binary or unsupported extensions — spreadsheets, presentations, images, and archives (`.xlsx`, `.pptx`, `.png`, `.zip`, …) — are refused with exit `3` rather than raw-byte \"text\"-diffed into a meaningless report. An *unknown* extension whose first 8 KB contains a NUL byte is treated as binary and refused the same way. A file that is not valid UTF-8 is likewise refused with exit `3` rather than decoded with replacement characters (`�`): silent replacement can make two files that differ only in undecodable bytes look identical, hiding a real difference.\n\n  Line 47: If none is present, `compare`/`compare-pair` on a PDF exits `3` with an actionable message. The fallback is to extract the text yourself and run `compare-pair --before old.txt --after new.txt`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/references/README.md:\n  Line 8: | The baseline-before-edit workflow, the explicit-pair fallback, and snapshot lifecycle | [`workflow.md`](workflow.md) |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/feature-catalog/comparison-engine/multi-format-extraction.md:\n  Line 20: Every `compare` and `compare-pair` run starts here: the engine picks an extractor by file type, produces normalized text, and records the fidelity tier that later appears in the report summary. Text and Markdown are the only full-fidelity formats; HTML, DOCX, and PDF are text-only and carry an honest warning about what was dropped. The typical caller is the diff flow itself rather than a human, and the main failure mode is a format the extractor cannot read at all — handled by exiting `3` with a fallback message rather than emitting a misleading empty diff.\n\n  Line 28: PDF is conditional: the engine tries `pdftotext`, then `pypdf`, then `pdfplumber`, using whichever is present, and reports the `text*` tier. A scanned or image-only PDF with no text layer is flagged explicitly rather than silently producing an empty diff; OCR is out of scope. When no extractor can handle the input, the run exits `3` with an actionable message that points at the explicit-pair fallback.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/manual-testing-playbook/safety/capability-and-unsupported-handling.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"SAFE-004 -- Capability reporting and unsupported handling\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"This scenario validates capability reporting and unsupported handling for `SAFE-004`. It focuses on confirming `capabilities` reports the format matrix and detected PDF extractor, and that unsupported or limited cases fail honestly.\"\n\n  Line 8: # SAFE-004 -- Capability reporting and unsupported handling\n\n  Line 16: This scenario validates capability reporting and unsupported handling for `SAFE-004`. It focuses on confirming `capabilities` reports the format matrix and detected PDF extractor, and that unsupported or limited cases fail honestly.\n\n  Line 20: Trust in a comparison tool depends on it being honest about what it can and cannot do. Users need an accurate capability matrix — which formats compare at full fidelity, which at text fidelity, and whether a PDF extractor is even installed — and they need unsupported input to fail with exit `3` rather than a fabricated diff. This scenario proves `capabilities` reports the true five-format matrix and detected extractor, and that an unsupported format refuses cleanly instead of inventing a result.\n\n  Line 28: - Objective: confirm `capabilities` reports the format matrix and detected PDF extractor, and that an unsupported or limited case exits `3` rather than fabricating a diff\n\n  Line 31: - Expected execution process: the operator runs `capabilities` (and `capabilities --json`) to read the format/tier matrix and the detected PDF extractor, then attempts to compare an unsupported format and confirms the engine exits `3` with no report.\n\n  Line 32: - Expected signals: the five formats with their tiers (text=full, markdown=full, html=text, docx=text, pdf=text*) and the detected PDF extractor (or its absence); an unsupported comparison exits `3` and writes no report.\n\n  Line 33: - Desired user-visible outcome: an accurate capability matrix and honest failure on unsupported input.\n\n  Line 34: - Pass/fail: PASS if `capabilities` lists the five formats with correct tiers and the detected extractor, and the unsupported comparison exits `3` with no fabricated diff; FAIL if the matrix is wrong or incomplete, or the unsupported case produces a diff/report instead of exit `3`.\n\n  Line 48: 3. `python3 scripts/create_diff.py compare-pair --before /tmp/before.xlsx --after /tmp/after.xlsx --report /tmp/unsupported.html`\n\n  Line 52: Step 1 prints the format matrix listing text (full), markdown (full), html (text), docx (text), and pdf (text*), plus the detected PDF extractor or a note that none is available. Step 2 emits the same information as a JSON object suitable for scripting, consistent with the step 1 human output. Step 3, given an unsupported format such as `.xlsx`, exits `3` with a message that the format is unsupported and writes no `/tmp/unsupported.html` — it does not fabricate a diff. (Supply the two `.xlsx` inputs, or substitute any other unsupported format.)\n\n  Line 66: 2. Confirm the step 3 input is genuinely an unsupported format and confirm the exit code is exactly `3` (unsupported), not `5` (I/O/extraction failure).\n\n  Line 94: - Feature file path: `safety/capability-and-unsupported-handling.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/feature-catalog/snapshot-lifecycle/explicit-pair-comparison.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Compares two explicit files with no stored state — the fallback for arbitrary versions or a missing baseline.\"\n\n  Line 18: Compares two explicit files with no stored state — the fallback when no baseline exists or when comparing two arbitrary versions.\n\n  Line 46: | `manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md` | Manual playbook | CMP-001 runs `compare-pair` on the fixtures; SNAP-002 exercises the missing-baseline fallback into `compare-pair` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/manual-testing-playbook/comparison/pdf-text-comparison.md:\n  Line 31: - Expected execution process: the operator first checks `capabilities` for a detected PDF extractor, then supplies two small text-based PDFs; with an extractor present the engine extracts and compares the text layer via `compare-pair` and writes a report; with no extractor present the engine exits `3` and points the user at the explicit-pair fallback.\n\n  Line 52: Step 1 shows the format matrix including the detected PDF extractor (or none). When step 1 reports an extractor, step 2 prints a `Compared before.pdf → after.pdf (pdf, tier text*)` summary with counts and a written report, exiting `0`, and step 3 returns `PASS`. When step 1 reports no extractor, step 2 exits `3` with an actionable message pointing to the explicit-pair fallback, writes no report, and step 3 is skipped. (Before step 2, supply two small text-based — not scanned — PDFs at `/tmp/before.pdf` and `/tmp/after.pdf`; there are no shipped `.pdf` fixtures.)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/feature-catalog/snapshot-lifecycle/baseline-snapshot-and-compare.md:\n  Line 20: This is the primary lifecycle for reviewing an edit whose \"before\" state would otherwise be lost. A caller runs `snapshot` on a file first, lets an edit happen, then runs `compare` to see what changed against the stored baseline. The store is local and content-addressed, and the source file is only ever read, so the invariant a caller relies on is that snapshotting can never mutate or lose their document. The main failure mode — running `compare` with no baseline captured — exits `4` and routes to the explicit-pair fallback rather than guessing.\n\n  Line 56: - [explicit-pair-comparison.md](explicit-pair-comparison.md) — the stateless fallback when no baseline was captured\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/manual-testing-playbook/snapshot/missing-baseline-fallback.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"SNAP-002 -- Missing baseline routes to fallback\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"This scenario validates missing-baseline fallback for `SNAP-002`. It focuses on confirming `compare` with no stored baseline exits `4` and that the explicit-pair fallback works instead.\"\n\n  Line 8: # SNAP-002 -- Missing baseline routes to fallback\n\n  Line 16: This scenario validates missing-baseline fallback for `SNAP-002`. It focuses on confirming `compare` with no stored baseline exits `4` and that the explicit-pair fallback works instead.\n\n  Line 28: - Objective: confirm `compare` with no stored baseline exits `4` with guidance, and that the explicit-pair fallback produces a report instead\n\n  Line 31: - Expected execution process: the operator runs `compare` against an empty state store so no baseline exists; the engine exits `4` with a \"no baseline\" message pointing to the explicit-pair fallback; the operator then runs `compare-pair` with two explicit files, which produces a report the validator confirms safe.\n\n  Line 33: - Desired user-visible outcome: a clear \"no baseline\" message and a working fallback path.\n\n  Line 34: - Pass/fail: PASS if `compare` exits `4` with guidance and writes no report, and `compare-pair` then produces a report that validates `PASS`; FAIL if `compare` fabricates a diff, exits with a different code, or the fallback fails to produce a valid report.\n\n  Line 52: Step 1, run against the empty state store `/tmp/empty-store` (no prior snapshot for the file), exits `4` and prints a \"no baseline\" message pointing the user at the explicit-pair fallback; no report is written. Step 2 compares two explicit files, prints a summary with change counts, writes `/tmp/pair.html`, and exits `0`. Step 3 prints `PASS` and exits `0`. (Supply `/tmp/a.md` and `/tmp/b.md` as two small files that differ.)\n\n  Line 56: Capture the step 1 stdout and its exit code `4`, confirmation that no report file was written by step 1, the step 2 summary and report path, and the step 3 validator verdict. Record the two fallback inputs used.\n\n  Line 67: 3. Confirm `/tmp/a.md` and `/tmp/b.md` exist and differ so the fallback in step 2 produces a non-empty, valid report.\n\n  Line 94: - Feature file path: `snapshot/missing-baseline-fallback.md`\n","metadata":{"matches":69,"truncated":false},"title":"container-name:report|@container report|cqi|unsupported|fallback","time":{"start":1784210833250,"end":1784210833269}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09a0b1a9d171929b016a58e5910c4881919effbe186fa660cb"}},"id":"prt_f6b40bf5f001uYIWktNeUvETDT","sessionID":"ses_094c57e18ffemFIYitl0QMkdbq","messageID":"msg_f6b4036d7001RFUSs0WhB9jSBR"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784210833273,"sessionID":"ses_094c57e18ffemFIYitl0QMkdbq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_ciQSc7mrFDQQJGTK1DpfoV4a","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff","pattern":"cleanup|dry-run|manifest|state-dir","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 61 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/SKILL.md:\n  Line 167: python3 scripts/create_diff.py cleanup --older-than 14      # prune old baselines (add --dry-run to preview)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/scripts/README.md:\n  Line 49: | `create_diff.py` | Diff engine and report renderer. Subcommands: `capabilities`, `snapshot`, `compare`, `compare-pair`, `status`, `cleanup`. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/changelog/v1.1.0.0.md:\n  Line 18:   - Content-addressed baseline snapshots (`snapshot`/`compare`), an explicit-pair fallback (`compare-pair`), and lifecycle commands (`status`, `cleanup`, `capabilities`).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/references/cli-reference.md:\n  Line 31: python3 create_diff.py snapshot <file> [--state-dir DIR]\n\n  Line 40:   [--report OUT] [--view unified|side-by-side] [--state-dir DIR] [--json]\n\n  Line 61: python3 create_diff.py status [<file>] [--state-dir DIR] [--json]\n\n  Line 64: ## `cleanup`\n\n  Line 69: python3 create_diff.py cleanup \\\n\n  Line 70:   [--file F] [--older-than DAYS] [--state-dir DIR] [--dry-run]\n\n  Line 73: With no `--older-than`, all matching snapshots are removed. Use `--dry-run` to preview.\n\n  Line 81: | `--state-dir DIR` | snapshot, compare, status, cleanup | Snapshot store location (default `./.create-diff`). |\n\n  Line 84: | `--older-than DAYS` | cleanup | Remove snapshots older than N days. |\n\n  Line 85: | `--dry-run` | cleanup | Preview removals without deleting. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/feature-catalog/feature-catalog.md:\n  Line 117: `status` lists snapshots (all or per-file); `cleanup` removes them by age (`--older-than`) or wholesale, with `--dry-run` to preview; state lives under `.create-diff/` and is safe to delete.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/references/workflow.md:\n  Line 3: description: The capture-before-edit invariant, the automatic snapshot flow, the explicit-pair fallback, snapshot storage, and cleanup lifecycle for create-diff.\n\n  Line 8:   - \"snapshot cleanup lifecycle\"\n\n  Line 49: Baselines are stored under a `.create-diff/` directory in the current working directory (override with `--state-dir DIR`). Each source path gets its own subdirectory keyed by a hash of its absolute path, containing the copied blobs plus a `manifest.json` recording capture time, size, and SHA-256. Writes are atomic (temp file + rename); the source is only ever read.\n\n  Line 61: python3 ../scripts/create_diff.py cleanup --older-than 14 --dry-run\n\n  Line 62: python3 ../scripts/create_diff.py cleanup --older-than 14\n\n  Line 65: `cleanup` with no `--older-than` removes all matching snapshots; scope it with `--file` and preview with `--dry-run`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md:\n  Line 266: ### SNAP-003 | Snapshot status and cleanup\n\n  Line 269: Verify that stored baselines can be listed and pruned safely, with a dry-run preview.\n\n  Line 274: Run `status` (expect a listing), then `cleanup --older-than N --dry-run` (expect a preview with no deletion), then `cleanup --older-than N` (expect removal).\n\n  Line 276: Desired user-visible outcome: an accurate snapshot listing and a safe, previewable cleanup.\n\n  Line 279: > **Feature File:** [SNAP-003](snapshot/snapshot-status-and-cleanup.md)\n\n  Line 379: | SNAP-003 | Snapshot status and cleanup | SNAPSHOT | [SNAP-003](snapshot/snapshot-status-and-cleanup.md) |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/feature-catalog/snapshot-lifecycle/snapshot-state-management.md:\n  Line 7:   - \"cleanup old snapshots\"\n\n  Line 8:   - \"status and cleanup\"\n\n  Line 12: # Snapshot state management (status / cleanup)\n\n  Line 20: This is the housekeeping half of the snapshot lifecycle. A caller uses `status` to see which baselines exist and `cleanup` to remove ones they no longer need, keeping the local `.create-diff/` store from growing without limit. The store is plain files and is always safe to delete wholesale, so the main risk this feature guards against is not data loss but accidental over-deletion — handled by the `--dry-run` preview before anything is actually removed.\n\n  Line 26: `status [<file>]` lists stored baselines: with no argument it reports every snapshot in the store, and with a file it scopes to that source. `--json` emits the same listing in machine-readable form, and `--state-dir` points at a non-default store.\n\n  Line 28: `cleanup` prunes baselines by age or wholesale: `--older-than DAYS` keeps recent snapshots and removes older ones, `--file F` scopes the prune to a single source, and running it without an age filter clears the matching snapshots entirely. `--dry-run` prints exactly what would be removed without deleting anything, so a caller can preview a prune first. Because the whole store under `.create-diff/` is disposable, deleting it by hand is an equally valid reset.\n\n  Line 38: | `scripts/create_diff.py` | Script | `status` lists snapshots (all or per-file); `cleanup` prunes by `--older-than DAYS` or wholesale with a `--dry-run` preview; state lives under `.create-diff/` and is safe to delete |\n\n  Line 39: | `references/workflow.md` | Shared | The snapshot storage layout and the cleanup lifecycle |\n\n  Line 45: | `manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md` | Manual playbook | SNAP-003 verifies listing, the `--dry-run` preview, and actual pruning |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/manual-testing-playbook/snapshot/snapshot-status-and-cleanup.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"SNAP-003 -- Snapshot status and cleanup\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"This scenario validates snapshot status and cleanup for `SNAP-003`. It focuses on listing stored baselines and pruning them safely with a dry-run preview before deletion.\"\n\n  Line 8: # SNAP-003 -- Snapshot status and cleanup\n\n  Line 16: This scenario validates snapshot status and cleanup for `SNAP-003`. It focuses on listing stored baselines and pruning them safely with a dry-run preview before deletion.\n\n  Line 20: The snapshot store accumulates baselines over time, and users need to see what is stored and reclaim space without accidentally deleting a baseline they still need. The safe contract is an accurate `status` listing plus a `cleanup` that previews exactly what it will remove under `--dry-run` before any destructive run. This scenario proves the listing is truthful and that the dry-run preview deletes nothing, so cleanup is always previewable and never a surprise.\n\n  Line 28: - Objective: list stored baselines and prune them safely, with a dry-run preview that deletes nothing before the real cleanup\n\n  Line 31: - Expected execution process: the operator seeds at least one snapshot, runs `status` to list stored baselines, runs `cleanup --older-than N --dry-run` to preview removals without deleting, then runs `cleanup --older-than N` to actually remove the qualifying baselines.\n\n  Line 32: - Expected signals: an accurate `status` listing, a `--dry-run` preview that reports what would be removed while leaving the store unchanged, and a real `cleanup` run that removes exactly the previewed baselines.\n\n  Line 33: - Desired user-visible outcome: an accurate snapshot listing and a safe, previewable cleanup.\n\n  Line 34: - Pass/fail: PASS if `status` lists the seeded baselines, the `--dry-run` preview leaves the store byte-unchanged, and the real `cleanup` removes exactly the previewed entries; FAIL if the listing is wrong, the dry-run deletes anything, or the real cleanup removes more or fewer entries than previewed.\n\n  Line 46: 1. `python3 scripts/create_diff.py snapshot /tmp/doc.md --state-dir /tmp/cd-store`\n\n  Line 47: 2. `python3 scripts/create_diff.py status --state-dir /tmp/cd-store`\n\n  Line 48: 3. `python3 scripts/create_diff.py cleanup --older-than N --dry-run --state-dir /tmp/cd-store`\n\n  Line 49: 4. `python3 scripts/create_diff.py cleanup --older-than N --state-dir /tmp/cd-store`\n\n  Line 57: Capture the step 2 `status` listing, the step 3 dry-run preview text, a listing of `/tmp/cd-store` immediately after step 3 proving nothing was deleted, the step 4 output, and a final `status` (or store listing) confirming the previewed baselines were removed. Record the value of `N` used.\n\n  Line 67: 2. Compare a listing of `/tmp/cd-store` taken before and immediately after step 3; any difference means the dry-run is not honoring its no-delete contract and is an immediate FAIL.\n\n  Line 68: 3. Confirm the same `--state-dir` is passed to every command so `status`, the dry-run, and the real cleanup all operate on the same store.\n\n  Line 95: - Feature file path: `snapshot/snapshot-status-and-cleanup.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/feature-catalog/snapshot-lifecycle/baseline-snapshot-and-compare.md:\n  Line 26: `snapshot <file>` copies the source into a local snapshot store — `./.create-diff/` by default, overridable with `--state-dir`. Each source gets its own subdirectory keyed by the sha256 of its absolute path, holding a content-addressed blob plus a `manifest.json`. Writes are atomic (temp file then `os.replace`), and the source document is only read, never written, which is what upholds the capture-before-edit invariant.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/manual-testing-playbook/safety/source-never-mutated.md:\n  Line 47: 2. `python3 scripts/create_diff.py snapshot /tmp/a.md --state-dir /tmp/cd-store`\n\n  Line 48: 3. `python3 scripts/create_diff.py compare /tmp/a.md --state-dir /tmp/cd-store --report /tmp/c.html`\n\n  Line 68: 2. Confirm the `--state-dir` and `--report` paths point outside the source files' locations so an output was not accidentally directed at a source path.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/manual-testing-playbook/snapshot/baseline-capture-then-compare.md:\n  Line 46: 1. `python3 scripts/create_diff.py snapshot /tmp/doc.md --state-dir /tmp/cd-store`\n\n  Line 47: 2. `python3 scripts/create_diff.py compare /tmp/doc.md --state-dir /tmp/cd-store --report /tmp/snap-diff.html`\n\n  Line 65: 1. Confirm the same `--state-dir` is passed to both `snapshot` and `compare`; a mismatched store makes `compare` see no baseline and exit `4`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-diff/manual-testing-playbook/snapshot/missing-baseline-fallback.md:\n  Line 46: 1. `python3 scripts/create_diff.py compare /tmp/nobaseline.md --state-dir /tmp/empty-store`\n","metadata":{"matches":61,"truncated":false},"title":"cleanup|dry-run|manifest|state-dir","time":{"start":1784210833253,"end":1784210833271}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09a0b1a9d171929b016a58e5910c5881918a7f6f9b6eaebdbb"}},"id":"prt_f6b40bf6200182AA72gh5T0mYK","sessionID":"ses_094c57e18ffemFIYitl0QMkdbq","messageID":"msg_f6b4036d7001RFUSs0WhB9jSBR"}}
